      ],
      "scripts": [
        {
          "number": 1,
          "script": "Welcome to this lesson on model theft and extraction risks. To understand why this matters, think about what goes into building a modern AI model. We're talking about months of work, vast amounts of data, enormous computing power, and in many cases, millions of pounds of investment. That makes these models genuinely valuable assets, and valuable assets attract thieves. Now, here's what makes this type of theft particularly interesting: an attacker doesn't need to break into your servers or steal your code directly. Instead, they can simply interact with your model, observe how it behaves, and gradually piece together its secrets from the outside. It's a bit like figuring out a secret recipe just by tasting the dish repeatedly. And once someone has effectively stolen your model, they can use it to undercut your business, build competing products, or sell it on. So throughout this lesson, we'll explore exactly how these attacks work and what you can do to protect against them."
        },
        {
          "number": 2,
          "script": "So, what exactly is model extraction? Well, imagine someone doesn't have direct access to your AI model, but they can still interact with it through an API or a public interface. What an attacker can do is send it hundreds, sometimes thousands, of carefully chosen queries, and then study the responses they get back. Over time, those responses start to reveal how the model behaves, what patterns it follows, and how it makes decisions. By collecting enough of these responses, the attacker can gradually piece together a replica of the original model. They're essentially training their own copy using your model's outputs as the training data. And here's the really concerning part: they never need to break in, steal any files, or access your infrastructure directly. The model itself, simply by doing its job and answering questions, leaks enough information to be duplicated. That's what makes this type of attack so subtle and so difficult to detect."
        },
        {
          "number": 3,
          "script": "So how exactly do attackers go about stealing a model? There are actually several techniques they use, and they range from quite straightforward to surprisingly sophisticated. The most common approach is simply bombarding a model with queries and using the responses to piece together how it makes decisions. From there, an attacker can train their own smaller model to copy the original's behaviour. Beyond that, some attacks try to figure out whether a particular piece of data was used in training, which raises serious privacy concerns. Others exploit subtle clues like how long a model takes to respond, or how much processing power it uses. At scale, even scraping a public API can yield enough responses to reconstruct a working replica. And in federated learning environments, where models are trained collaboratively, the updates being shared can accidentally leak details about the underlying model. So as you can see, the attack surface here is genuinely broad."
        },
        {
          "number": 4,
          "script": "One of the most accessible ways attackers try to steal a model is simply by talking to it, over and over again. By sending thousands of carefully crafted queries, they can start to map out how the model behaves across a wide range of situations. And here is the concerning part: the patterns in those responses gradually reveal the model's internal logic, where it draws its boundaries, and how it makes decisions. This kind of attack is surprisingly cheap to carry out, which makes it attractive to a broad range of bad actors. Over time, by probing the model across different types of inputs, an attacker can piece together enough information to build a functional replica. And you might assume that limiting access through a public API would offer some protection, but even that can leak enough detail to make this possible. So the model does not need to be directly accessed or stolen in the traditional sense; it can be reconstructed just through observation."
        },
        {
          "number": 5,
          "script": "So now that we understand how model theft can happen, let's look at what you can actually do to defend against it. There are several practical measures worth putting in place. First, you can limit how many API calls someone is allowed to make in a given period, which makes it much harder to run those bulk query attacks we talked about. You can also watermark your model's outputs, so if your model does get copied, you have a way to trace it back. It's worth monitoring for unusual query patterns too, because suspicious behaviour often leaves a trail. Restricting access so that only authorised users and systems can interact with your model is another sensible step. You might also consider adding a small amount of noise to your predictions, which obscures the model's internal behaviour without meaningfully affecting its usefulness. And finally, regularly auditing who is querying your model, and how frequently, helps you stay on top of anything that looks out of the ordinary."
        },
        {
          "number": 6,
          "script": "So now that we understand how model theft can happen, let's look at what you can actually do to protect yourself. The good news is there are some very practical measures you can put in place. First, think about controlling how many queries any single user or application can make in a given period. If someone is hammering your API with thousands of requests, that is a red flag, and rate limiting helps you slow that down. You can also embed invisible watermarks into your model's outputs, so if a stolen version surfaces somewhere, you have a way to trace it back. Beyond that, keep a close eye on your access logs. Unusual patterns, like a sudden spike in requests or queries coming from unexpected locations, can be early warning signs. Auditing who is accessing your model and how often gives you visibility and accountability. None of these steps are complicated, but together they make extraction significantly harder for anyone attempting it."
        },
        {
          "number": 7,
          "script": "So now that we understand how model theft can happen, let's look at what you can actually do to defend against it. There are several practical measures worth putting in place. First, you can limit how many API calls a user or system can make in a given period, which makes it much harder for an attacker to systematically probe your model. You can also watermark your outputs, so if a stolen model surfaces somewhere, you have a way to trace it back. Monitoring your query logs for unusual patterns is equally important, because strange or repetitive requests are often a warning sign. Locking down access with proper authentication and role-based permissions means only the right people can interact with your model in the first place. You can also introduce small, deliberate variations in your outputs to reduce the accuracy of anything an attacker might extract. And finally, make a habit of auditing your logs regularly so nothing slips through unnoticed."
        },
        {
          "number": 8,
          "script": "So let's bring everything together from this lesson. The core thing to remember is that model theft is a real and practical threat, not just a theoretical one. Attackers can systematically query a model and essentially reconstruct it, and even the outputs your model produces can leak sensitive information about how it was built and trained. On the defensive side, watermarking gives you a way to detect if your model has been copied, which is genuinely useful. You also want to be thoughtful about who gets API access and under what conditions, because limiting that access reduces your exposure significantly. Keeping an eye on unusual query patterns is equally important, since strange or repetitive requests are often a warning sign that something is wrong. And finally, if you do spot something suspicious, report it straight away. The faster you act, the better your chances of containing any damage. These are the principles worth holding onto as we move forward."
        }
      ]
